    <string name="support_resources">Support resources</string>
    <string name="support_resources_body">Emergency: 000 in Australia.\nPoisons Information: 13 11 26.\nLifeline: 13 11 14.\n\nDrugDiary should keep these references local and editable for each region.</string>
    <string name="support_principle">App principle: support resources should be fast to access, non-judgemental, region-aware, and available without sending private data anywhere.</string>
    <string name="support_resources_subtitle">Fast access to crisis support, drug education, harm-reduction references, mental health grounding, and local DrugDiary tools. External links open without sharing profile data.</string>
    <string name="support_immediate_help_title">Immediate help</string>
    <string name="support_immediate_help_body">If someone may be in immediate danger, call local emergency services now. These shortcuts connect to crisis and poison services; DrugDiary does not send your profile or diary data with them.</string>
    <string name="support_substance_treatment_title">Drug and mental health support</string>
    <string name="support_substance_treatment_body">Confidential treatment locators, helplines, and evidence-based drug information for substance use, mental health, alcohol, and medication concerns.</string>
    <string name="support_harm_reduction_title">Harm-reduction education</string>
    <string name="support_harm_reduction_body">Independent education resources for substance effects, testing, safer-use planning, dose cautions, and risk awareness. Use these as education, not as proof that any substance is safe.</string>
    <string name="support_app_tools_title">DrugDiary tools</string>
    <string name="support_app_tools_body">Open the app tools that can help review combinations, calculations, and reagent references while keeping your profile-local data private.</string>
    <string name="support_urgent_warning_title">When to seek urgent care</string>
    <string name="support_urgent_warning_body">Get urgent help for chest pain, difficulty breathing, seizure, loss of consciousness, severe confusion, blue or pale skin, overheating, severe agitation, suicidal thoughts, allergic reaction, or suspected overdose. If in doubt, call emergency services or poison control.</string>
    <string name="support_safer_use_title">Safer-use planning checklist</string>
    <string name="support_safer_use_body">Avoid mixing depressants, opioids, alcohol, stimulants, or unknown substances. Start low and wait long enough before redosing. Do not drive. Keep water, cooling, trusted support, and emergency contact options available. Test substances where legal and carry naloxone where opioid exposure is possible.</string>
    <string name="support_grounding_title">Mental health grounding</string>
    <string name="support_grounding_body">Move to a quieter space, lower stimulation, slow your breathing, sip water, and contact a trusted person. Do not take more substances to force the feeling to change. If you might hurt yourself or someone else, use crisis support or emergency services immediately.</string>
    <string name="support_privacy_boundary_title">Privacy boundary</string>
    <string name="support_privacy_boundary_body">This page is a local resource directory. Opening a link or dialer action does not attach encrypted profile data, medications, diary entries, assistant messages, or QR exports.</string>
